HTML tags and their descriptions:

1. {' '}Defines an HTML document.

2. {' '}Contains metadata information about the document, such as the title and links to CSS stylesheets.

3. {''}</b>Defines the title of the document, which appears in the browser's title bar or tab.</p> <p>4. <b>{'<body>'}</b>Contains the visible content of the document.</p> <p>5. <b>{'<h1> - <h6>'}</b> Defines headings of different levels of importance, with {'<h1>'}being the most important and{'<h6>'}being the least. </p> <p>6. <b>{'<p>'}</b>Defines a paragraph of text.</p> <p>7. <b>{'<a> '}</b>Defines a hyperlink to another web page or a specific location within the same page.</p> <p>8. <b>{'<img>'}</b>Inserts an image into the document.</p> <p>9. <b>{'<ul>'}</b> Defines an unordered list, typically marked with bullet points.</p> <p>10. <b>{'<ol>'}</b>Defines an ordered list, typically marked with numbers or letters.</p> <p>11. <b>{'<li>'}</b>Defines a list item within an ordered or unordered list.</p> <p>12. <b>{'<div>'}</b>Defines a container for HTML elements, which can be used for styling and positioning.</p> <p>13. <b>{'<span>'}</b> Defines a small container for inline HTML elements, which can be used for styling and positioning.</p> <p>14. <b>{'<form>'}</b>Defines a form for user input, which can contain various input fields and submit buttons.</p> <p>15. <b>{'<input>'}</b>Defines an input field for user input, such as a text box or a checkbox.</p> <p>16. <b>{'<button>'}</b>Defines a clickable button element, which can be used for various user interactions.</p> <p>17. <b>{'<select>'}</b>Defines a dropdown list, which allows users to select one or more options.</p> <p>14. <b>{'<option>'}</b>Defines an option within a dropdown list.</p> <p>15. <b>{'<textarea>'}</b>Defines a multi-line text input field.</p> <p>16. <b>{'<hr>'}</b>tag: The {'<hr>'} tag stands for "horizontal rule". It is used to insert a horizontal line in the HTML page. The line can be used to separate content visually.</p> <p>17. <b>{'<br>'}</b>tag: The {'<br>'} tag stands for "line break". It is used to insert a line break or a new line in the HTML content. Unlike the {'<p>'} tag which creates a new paragraph, the {'<br>'} tag only creates a new line.</p> <h2>HTML Table Tags and Attributes</h2> <p>1.<b>{'<table>'}</b>tag: The {'<table>'} ag is used to define the start and end of an HTML table. All table-related tags are contained within the {'<table>'} element.</p> <p>2. <b>{'<caption>'}</b>tag: The {'<caption>'} tag is used to provide a title or caption for the table. It should be placed immediately after the opening {'<table>'} tag.</p> <p>3. <b>{'<frame>'}</b> attribute: The {'<frame>'} attribute specifies how the table borders should be displayed. It has three possible values: void, above, and below.</p> <p>4. <b>{'<rules>'}</b>attribute: The {'<rules>'} attribute specifies the visibility of the table's borders. It can be set to "none" to hide the borders, "groups" to display borders between row groups and column groups, or "rows" to display borders between rows.</p> <p>5. <b>{'<border>'}</b>attribute: The {'<border>'} attribute specifies the width of the table's borders in pixels.</p> <p>6. <b>{'<cellspacing>'}</b> attribute: The {'<cellspacing>'} attribute specifies the amount of space between adjacent cells in the table. It is specified in pixels.</p> <p>7. <b>{'<cellpadding>'}</b>attribute: The {'<cellpadding> '} attribute specifies the amount of space between the cell content and the cell borders. It is also specified in pixels.</p> <p>8. <b>{'<tr>'}</b>tag: The {'<tr>'} tag defines a table row.</p> <p>9. <b>{'<th>'}</b>tag: The {'<th>'} tag defines a table header cell. This is typically used to provide headings for each column in the table.</p> <p>10. <b>{'<td>'}</b>tag: The {'<td>'}tag defines a table data cell. This is where the actual content of the table is placed.</p> <h2>Links or Hypertext references</h2> <p>Links or hypertext references in HTML are used to create clickable elements on a web page that allow users to navigate to other pages, sections of the same page, or other online resources. The basic structure of a link consists of an anchor tag {'(<a>)'} and an href attribute that specifies the destination of the link.</p> <p>Here's an example of a basic link in HTML</p> <p>{'<a href="https://www.example.com">Click here to visit Example.com</a>'}</p> <p>In this example, the text "Click here to visit Example.com" is the clickable part of the link, while the href attribute specifies the URL of the destination. When the user clicks on the link, they will be taken to the website at the specified URL.</p> <p>Links can also be used to create anchor points within a single web page. This allows users to quickly jump to a specific section of the page by clicking on a link. To create an anchor point, you would add an <b>id</b> attribute to the element that you want to link to, and then create a link with a <b>#</b>symbol followed by the <b>id</b> value as the destination</p> <p>{'<h2 id="section1">Section 1</h2>'}</p> <p>{'<p>This is the first section of the page.</p>'}</p> <p>{'<h2 id="section2">Section 2</h2>'}</p> <p>{'<p>This is the second section of the page.</p>'}</p> <p>{'<a href="#section1">Go to Section 1</a>'}</p> <p>{'<a href="#section2">Go to Section 2</a>'}</p> <p>In this example, we've added <b>id</b> attributes to the two <b>h2</b> tags to create anchor points for each section. The two links at the bottom of the page use the <b>href</b> attribute to link to these anchor points, allowing users to quickly jump to a specific section of the page.</p> </div> ) } export default Html_2
